00:02:33.689 --> 00:02:38.890
water because I have what is called 'anti
technology karma'.

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:44.340
[laughter] Anybody who shows me how to do
something on a computer when I do the same

00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:45.859
functions, it doesn't work.

00:02:45.859 --> 00:02:51.700
Took me ten minutes to get out of the parking
lot at the Hilton this morning up at Burlingame

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:55.489
because the room key card would not work in
the -- you know, I watched the other cards

00:02:55.489 --> 00:02:59.099
in front of me all go through, put it in and
run out, put it in and run out, mine it doesn't

00:02:59.099 --> 00:03:00.590
work and so the gate doesn't come up.

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:02.650
So it takes me ten minutes to get out of the
parking lot.

00:03:02.650 --> 00:03:04.790
That's just the way my life is, you know.

00:03:04.790 --> 00:03:08.510
But I sure can make dancing earthworms.

00:03:08.510 --> 00:03:09.700
[laughter]

00:03:09.700 --> 00:03:17.930
&gt;&gt;Joel: And in the continuum of things probably
most of us, historically and in the future,

00:03:17.930 --> 00:03:23.760
will be far more dependent on dancing earthworms
than working key card slots out of a Hilton

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:26.769
parking lot.

00:03:26.769 --> 00:03:34.400
So -- and as my life has gone, on I have found
myself more and more kind of -- I call it

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:42.489
archaic-- in our culture because we live on
a farm that is -- that has four generations

00:03:42.489 --> 00:03:43.939
living on it.

00:03:43.939 --> 00:03:48.650
My mother is a very healthy happy octogenarian
will be 88 this winter.

00:03:48.650 --> 00:03:52.049
She still rides five miles a day on her stationary
bike.

00:03:52.049 --> 00:03:53.049
Drives.

00:03:53.049 --> 00:03:54.049
Ballroom dances.

00:03:54.049 --> 00:03:58.040
Teaches English country dancing to people
and sings in the Happy Notes which is an old

00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:04.109
-- it's a group of retirees-- who entertains
and she'll pop in at our house and she drives

00:04:04.109 --> 00:04:07.299
to sing in this chorus at the nursing home.

00:04:07.299 --> 00:04:11.519
She says, "we're going to sing to the old
folks" and half of them are younger than she

00:04:11.519 --> 00:04:12.519
is.

00:04:12.519 --> 00:04:15.969
But and then of course we have, you know,
Teresa and I are there and our children are

00:04:15.969 --> 00:04:18.060
there and their children are there.

00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:24.400
So we have four generations on the farm all
living in a commune.

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:25.400
It's quite dramatic.

00:04:25.400 --> 00:04:26.400
It's quite amazing.

00:04:26.400 --> 00:04:27.740
And we grow our own food.

00:04:27.740 --> 00:04:32.270
I feel like we just live in this nest of abundance.

00:04:32.270 --> 00:04:40.710
We live in a time when a lot of people are
concerned that we're teetering on the precipice

00:04:40.710 --> 00:04:43.949
of precariousness in a lot of things.

00:04:43.949 --> 00:04:51.270
You know, economically, ecologically, socially,
culturally.

00:04:51.270 --> 00:05:01.930
And so, to live surrounded by a tribe that
is devoted to a common denominator and surrounded

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:06.669
by abundance.

00:05:06.669 --> 00:05:07.729
We like to graze.

00:05:07.729 --> 00:05:09.360
I like to walk through the seasons.

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:15.030
We have mulberries and pawpaws and pear trees
and apple trees and grapes and strawberries

00:05:15.030 --> 00:05:16.280
and I just like to graze.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:24.270
I just have these visions of campuses whether
they're Google campuses or any kind of institutional

00:05:24.270 --> 00:05:29.520
campuses where all the ornamental landscaping
is converted to edible landscaping and you

00:05:29.520 --> 00:05:33.740
use your GPS technology to just let everybody
know every morning when you get up with a

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:38.509
app the strawberries in quadrant 45 are ready
to be picked today.

00:05:38.509 --> 00:05:43.280
[laughter] The asparagus in quadrant 87 pick
some spears on your way to your office this

00:05:43.280 --> 00:05:44.710
morning.

00:05:44.710 --> 00:05:45.990
Why couldn't we do that?

00:05:45.990 --> 00:05:54.199
And the idea is to return us as a nest -- as
a nest to an ecological womb.

00:05:54.199 --> 00:05:59.610
Wouldn't that do a lot to take the edge off
of the fear and the concern that many of us

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:03.610
have for some of the big picture items around
our world.

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:08.000
You know, we could hook up the exercise room
to water pumps that would pump water back

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:14.030
up on to the roofs of all of our buildings
that are growing strawberries and cucumbers.

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:19.189
That way we don't have to have any air-conditioning
and it cools down our buildings so much we

00:06:19.189 --> 00:06:22.409
use our human power to pump the water back
up on the roof.

00:06:22.409 --> 00:06:23.760
And this stuff can be done.

00:06:23.760 --> 00:06:26.520
It's not out of the question.

00:06:26.520 --> 00:06:32.909
So, as I live the more live the more I look
at our culture and I look at the fact that

00:06:32.909 --> 00:06:40.780
we are if first culture in human civilization
that routinely eats unpronounceable food.

00:06:40.780 --> 00:06:45.039
You know, we're the first culture in human
civilization that eats food that you can't

00:06:45.039 --> 00:06:46.439
make in your kitchen.

00:06:46.439 --> 00:06:49.439
You ever try to make high fructose corn syrup
in your kitchen?

00:06:49.439 --> 00:06:58.290
We're the first culture in the world, in history,
that has ever put 1500 miles on average under

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:00.740
every morsel of food.

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:01.990
That's a long ways.

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:08.909
You know, in 1930, one calorie of food on
the table took an average quarter calorie

00:07:08.909 --> 00:07:09.909
to get there.

00:07:09.909 --> 00:07:14.460
Today every calorie of food on the table takes
15 calories of energy to get there.

00:07:14.460 --> 00:07:19.760
I mean, these are hockey sticks graphs.

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:24.740
And we all know that hockey stick graphs never
last.

00:07:24.740 --> 00:07:33.371
And so, what happened was -- I'm leading up
to why this book came out -- was that as I

00:07:33.371 --> 00:07:42.349
tried to describe looking for sound bites
of how do I describe what I think has sustained

00:07:42.349 --> 00:07:49.139
and rejuvenated and regenerated and formed
the glue for human existence for centuries

00:07:49.139 --> 00:08:00.310
if not millennia, what I found was that this
blip that we call "modern America" is extremely

00:08:00.310 --> 00:08:02.850
abnormal.

00:08:02.850 --> 00:08:08.030
And I run into young people every day like
you know -- it's so fun to talk to a group

00:08:08.030 --> 00:08:09.030
here at Google.

00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:15.530
You know, if I talk to a group of farmers,
you know the average farmer is now 60 years

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:16.530
old.

00:08:16.530 --> 00:08:21.639
And they can remember, you know, a day before
supermarkets.

00:08:21.639 --> 00:08:27.009
Today most of us can't even remember a day
before computers.

00:08:27.009 --> 00:08:29.389
My first book -- I wrote on a typewriter.

00:08:29.389 --> 00:08:33.500
You know, when I was in college, there was
no computer.

00:08:33.500 --> 00:08:36.880
I wish you'd just think about this for a minute.

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:40.630
I can remember when TV dinners were introduced.

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:47.459
Can you imagine, you know, no microwave.

00:08:47.459 --> 00:08:52.040
I can remember a day when there was no takeout.

00:08:52.040 --> 00:08:57.960
I could remember when a salad bar buffet started
in restaurants.

00:08:57.960 --> 00:09:01.020
Started during Vietnam era -- Vietnam war
era.

00:09:01.020 --> 00:09:03.670
It was one of the biggest shocks of Vietnam
war veterans.

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:06.190
They went, they came back there were salad
bar restaurants.

00:09:06.190 --> 00:09:08.090
[laughter] Where did this come from?

00:09:08.090 --> 00:09:09.490
It was like boom!

00:09:09.490 --> 00:09:13.150
It hit the culture.

00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:17.360
But these are new things in our culture.

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:25.600
And as I would explain these things and how,
you know, when I was a kid if you wanted to

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:29.900
stay warm in the wintertime you don't have
to worry about this in California but where

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:36.410
we are if you want to stay warm in the wintertime
you had to get some heat in your house and

00:09:36.410 --> 00:09:38.290
so, we would cut wood.

00:09:38.290 --> 00:09:40.670
We had wood stoves and we would cut wood.

00:09:40.670 --> 00:09:48.730
And my wife has inherited her grandmother's
majestic wood cook stove that when she and

00:09:48.730 --> 00:09:57.300
granddaddy went to housekeeping in 1929, that
was state of the art technology -- this majestic

00:09:57.300 --> 00:10:03.699
wood cook stove that you put little kindling
on the side that's where your dish water got

00:10:03.699 --> 00:10:04.699
hot.

00:10:04.699 --> 00:10:06.570
It just kept hot water there all the time.

00:10:06.570 --> 00:10:11.610
You see all the old westerns and the baby
is getting ready to come and the doctor says

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:14.040
boil water.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:15.230
The water was always there.

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:16.949
It was always ready.

00:10:16.949 --> 00:10:19.860
That was new technology at that time.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:25.680
And so, I just started mentioning this as
I would describe these numerous things that

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:31.560
we've come to today with supermarkets with
unpronounceable food, with computers, with

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:42.440
the technology, you know, iPhones and iPads
and Google. that this represents an abnormal

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:45.550
blip in human history.

00:10:45.550 --> 00:10:51.100
And so, what is this glue that is normal in
civilization?

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:54.570
And so, I want to just spend a couple of minutes
and we'll go right to questions and answer

00:10:54.570 --> 00:11:00.120
and discussion about some of these things
that I think have been -- are interesting.

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:03.300
They're in the book 'Folks, This Ain't Normal'.

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:07.930
It describes what I consider to be abnormalities
in our system.

00:11:07.930 --> 00:11:12.270
You see -- historic -- so I want to talk about
animals for a minute.

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.950
Because animals are much-maligned in our culture.

00:11:14.950 --> 00:11:23.010
I got one chapter in the book the title something
like 'my aunt is my dog is my cat is my child'.

00:11:23.010 --> 00:11:28.170
And what we've done in our culture, as we
have Bambi-eyed and Disney-fied our culture,

00:11:28.170 --> 00:11:35.940
and we ascribe anthropomorphistic humanism
to animals and so, we have animal rights movement

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:39.139
that has eliminated, for example, wearing
fur.

00:11:39.139 --> 00:11:45.360
When I was a kid, teenagers would actually
get their spending money by trapping foxes

00:11:45.360 --> 00:11:47.800
and mink and beavers and stuff.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:48.800
I'm not that old.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:51.800
I'm not that old!

00:11:51.800 --> 00:11:52.820
I'm really 80.

00:11:52.820 --> 00:11:55.779
That's what good food does to you.

00:11:55.779 --> 00:12:01.532
[laughter] People would -- you know, I remember
very well old-timers saying back in the 20s

00:12:01.532 --> 00:12:02.532
and 30s.

00:12:02.532 --> 00:12:08.860
You know, when I was a boy these are people
that are old enough to be my dad in a community,

00:12:08.860 --> 00:12:14.940
this is how teens got money to go to the movies
or get their first automobile or whatever.

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:17.970
And fox skins brought 50 dollars apiece.

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:23.600
Today they're less than a dollar so nobody
traps and a lot of places in our country now

00:12:23.600 --> 00:12:26.390
are having problems with kids with rabies.

00:12:26.390 --> 00:12:32.320
One in ten foxes has the mange because of
this explosion because we've extracted humans

00:12:32.320 --> 00:12:35.410
out of nature.

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:40.019
And so, what was the role of animals historically?

00:12:40.019 --> 00:12:42.149
Let's talk about chickens.

00:12:42.149 --> 00:12:45.250
Historically chickens -- because everybody
likes chickens.

00:12:45.250 --> 00:12:52.080
I mean, chickens are like the most -- the
coolest of the farm animals.

00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:55.779
[laughter] So what was the role of chickens?

00:12:55.779 --> 00:13:03.490
Well, historically they didn't have garbage
trucks and landfills.

00:13:03.490 --> 00:13:09.870
And enough excess food to just throw it away.

00:13:09.870 --> 00:13:17.769
So chickens were a garbage disposal, salvage
operation in the homestead and the farm stead.

00:13:17.769 --> 00:13:19.149
That's what chickens were.

00:13:19.149 --> 00:13:26.550
And that's one reason why peasants -- chickens
were a luxury because there was no grain.

00:13:26.550 --> 00:13:29.190
Now, let me talk about grain for a minute.

00:13:29.190 --> 00:13:33.519
Because our culture -- when you think "farm,"
you tend to think "grain."

00:13:33.519 --> 00:13:35.009
That's what we think in our culture.

00:13:35.009 --> 00:13:43.480
In fact, we subsidize the U.S. duh Don't look
at me like you don't get this.

00:13:43.480 --> 00:13:48.620
The USDA subsidizes six types of grain annual
production.

00:13:48.620 --> 00:13:55.709
But in a day before cheap energy and machinery,
if you wanted to plow a field to grow barley

00:13:55.709 --> 00:14:05.070
or wheat, you had to walk all day behind ox
or a yak or a mule or a horse with a sharp

00:14:05.070 --> 00:14:09.959
stick and it was arduous work.

00:14:09.959 --> 00:14:13.529
And you know at the end of the day you looked
back and maybe the area of a size of this

00:14:13.529 --> 00:14:17.149
room you actually got torn up a little bit.

00:14:17.149 --> 00:14:21.160
And then you could go back and you could hand
broadcast seeds.

00:14:21.160 --> 00:14:22.190
Okay?

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:23.690
And those seeds would grow.

00:14:23.690 --> 00:14:28.720
And then you had to hand weed those seeds
to keep the weeds out of them then whatever

00:14:28.720 --> 00:14:33.940
grew, you could go in with a scythe and scythe
it down and then put in a shock so it could

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:34.940
dry.

00:14:34.940 --> 00:14:42.529
It actually ferments just a little bit because
of the uneven moisture drying of the stalk.

00:14:42.529 --> 00:14:49.470
And that's one reason why people now have
so much wheat gluten intolerance is because

00:14:49.470 --> 00:14:55.010
we're harvesting it so fast and drying it
so fast there's no tiny amount of fermentation

00:14:55.010 --> 00:15:01.670
that occurs in the grain, to change the enzymes
to digestible enzymes in the grain crop.

00:15:01.670 --> 00:15:03.089
Okay?

00:15:03.089 --> 00:15:04.509
So.

00:15:04.509 --> 00:15:12.100
You put it in a shock and then you took it
in to a hard floor maybe a wooden planks or

00:15:12.100 --> 00:15:16.480
beaten lime or rock or clay that you pounded
real hard.

00:15:16.480 --> 00:15:20.850
Anyway a hard surface and then you beat it
all right with a flail and then you would

00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:24.130
winnow it, all right, throw it up and the
breeze would blow through it and drive the

00:15:24.130 --> 00:15:28.940
chaff and husks away and then you'd get some
barley.

00:15:28.940 --> 00:15:34.110
Now carefully sweep that up and put it now
in a -- in something that you could store

00:15:34.110 --> 00:15:39.850
it away from rats and mice in a day before
sheet metal, before mesh metal, in a clay

00:15:39.850 --> 00:15:44.140
pot somewhere and hopefully that would last
you until the next year's harvest.

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:51.339
Folks, there was not enough grain left over
to feed animals.

00:15:51.339 --> 00:15:56.540
That's why in the Bible, in Hosea, the prophet
talks about a harlot being sold for 9 and

00:15:56.540 --> 00:15:58.250
a half ephahs of barley.

00:15:58.250 --> 00:16:00.290
It's not because harlots were cheap.

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:04.290
[laughter] It's because barley was expensive.

00:16:04.290 --> 00:16:13.729
[laughter] I'm trying to help us understand
here that this idea of cheap grain fundamentally

00:16:13.729 --> 00:16:20.920
-- fundamentally changed the role and the
place of farm animals that had been normal

00:16:20.920 --> 00:16:22.770
throughout history.

00:16:22.770 --> 00:16:28.930
And so, now suddenly we had all this grain
with our ability to tillage, machinery, cheap

00:16:28.930 --> 00:16:29.930
energy.

00:16:29.930 --> 00:16:32.410
And so, now we can go plow up with a great
machine.

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:38.460
Suddenly the traditional role of a chicken
which was right next to the kitchen to eat

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:46.200
the kitchen scraps and the, you know, the
peelings and all the stuff that came out spoiled

00:16:46.200 --> 00:16:47.620
food being in a day before refrigeration.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:50.010
Food spoiled what do you do?

00:16:50.010 --> 00:16:51.139
You feed it to chickens.

00:16:51.139 --> 00:16:56.279
And then chickens then in return then cycle
it -- the ultimate recycling agent-- and give

00:16:56.279 --> 00:16:58.949
us eggs in return.

00:16:58.949 --> 00:17:01.930
That was the traditional role of chickens.

00:17:01.930 --> 00:17:07.970
Today, we think we're great when we take our
banana peels and our waste from the kitchens,

00:17:07.970 --> 00:17:13.790
put it on a truck run with diesel power --especially
biodiesel-- and truck it off site somewhere

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:20.439
to a composting operation and then people
can buy the compost for their house plants

00:17:20.439 --> 00:17:22.329
or little ornamental flowers.

00:17:22.329 --> 00:17:27.689
What really would be green would be to attach
a chicken house next to each cafe so that

00:17:27.689 --> 00:17:34.299
the scraps [applause] went right into the
chicken house, the eggs come right back in

00:17:34.299 --> 00:17:38.220
and now we don't have to truck the garbage
anywhere or bring the eggs from anywhere.

00:17:38.220 --> 00:17:42.070
That's what I'm talking about is normal, okay?

00:17:42.070 --> 00:17:47.480
So, I've just concentrated on chickens but
you could take every single animal.

00:17:47.480 --> 00:17:51.179
I'll do one more just to show where I'm coming
from.

00:17:51.179 --> 00:17:52.570
Let's take cows.

00:17:52.570 --> 00:17:53.570
All right?

00:17:53.570 --> 00:17:57.660
What is the role of herbivores in nature?

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:01.780
Historically herbivores -- the bison on the
American plain.

00:18:01.780 --> 00:18:07.720
Today the wildebeest on the Serengeti, the
cape buffalo in Botswana.

00:18:07.720 --> 00:18:14.270
We Americans -- we modern day developed country
people-- are absolutely brain damaged when

00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:17.060
we talk about grass.

00:18:17.060 --> 00:18:22.540
When I say "grass," everybody thinks about
this close cropped lawn out here or a golf

00:18:22.540 --> 00:18:23.780
course, right?

00:18:23.780 --> 00:18:30.220
When I say "grass," what I think about grass,
is little house on the prairie when ma and

00:18:30.220 --> 00:18:35.809
pa wouldn't let the girls go out past the
stoop of the soddie lest they get lost.

00:18:35.809 --> 00:18:36.809
Lost?

00:18:36.809 --> 00:18:37.929
What do you mean?

00:18:37.929 --> 00:18:44.590
We think lost, the city beautification committee
would cite me for violating the ordinance

00:18:44.590 --> 00:18:46.570
for having an unkempt lawn.

00:18:46.570 --> 00:18:52.470
No, I'm talking about glass, like if you go
today to the University of Nebraska at Lincoln,

00:18:52.470 --> 00:18:58.270
they've preserved a 2-acre native prairie
patch they used it with fire.

00:18:58.270 --> 00:19:01.340
This grass is 12 feet tall.

00:19:01.340 --> 00:19:04.130
It's more than half an inch thick at the stem.

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:05.450
It's thick as hair on a dog's back.

00:19:05.450 --> 00:19:09.120
I still get chills every time I talk about
it.

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:18.960
It's an absolute biological biomass soil building
carbon sequestering cathedral.

00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:24.210
[laughter] And you walk out in there in this
12-foot tall grass.

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:27.740
I mean, taller than the lights in this room,
okay?

00:19:27.740 --> 00:19:30.820
And it's over your head and it just blocks
out the world.

00:19:30.820 --> 00:19:37.659
And then to imagine this rustling waving mass
of biomass for hundreds of miles out through

00:19:37.659 --> 00:19:38.659
the prairies.

00:19:38.659 --> 00:19:40.870
I mean, it is unbelievable.

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:50.260
And so, civilization -- civilizations coalesced
early on around grasses, perennials and herbivores

00:19:50.260 --> 00:19:57.180
because that was the only really nutrient
dense product that could be produced without

00:19:57.180 --> 00:19:58.590
tillage.

00:19:58.590 --> 00:20:07.740
Because when all tillage was done with a crude
stick or a wooden spade, it was too precious

00:20:07.740 --> 00:20:10.210
to do in any scale.

00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:17.150
And so, that's why lamb, goat, camel, cow,
yak -- all right?

00:20:17.150 --> 00:20:25.440
Became the centerpiece of civilizational diets
and fish all right?

00:20:25.440 --> 00:20:26.980
Because that could be fished.

00:20:26.980 --> 00:20:28.440
You didn't have to till to get seafood.

00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:31.090
And you didn't have to till to get the herbivore.

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:40.110
And so, that's why that became the centerpiece
of dietary protocol in every civilization.

00:20:40.110 --> 00:20:50.600
Today, with cheap grain, we have been able
to abdicate this and plow up everything and

00:20:50.600 --> 00:20:58.030
confine the animals in houses where they neither
salvage nor do anything except for eat erosive,

00:20:58.030 --> 00:21:09.809
petrol chemical dependent, ecologically debilitating,
annuals that are subsidized by U.S. domestic

00:21:09.809 --> 00:21:18.250
policy to make cheap food in concentrated
animal feeding operations that have no comparison

00:21:18.250 --> 00:21:26.480
either ecologically or relationally or symbiotically
or nutritionally to their forbearers who filled

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:34.779
a definite function in their ecology of the
ecological womb.

00:21:34.779 --> 00:21:40.480
So what we've been able to do is extricate
ourselves from this historic normalcy which

00:21:40.480 --> 00:21:45.010
was the herbivore is the biomass restart button.

00:21:45.010 --> 00:21:46.980
The grass grows in an S curve.

00:21:46.980 --> 00:21:48.530
You with me?

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:49.880
S curve.

00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:52.309
The bottom part I call diaper grass.

00:21:52.309 --> 00:21:55.500
This is teenage grass and this is nursing
home grass.

00:21:55.500 --> 00:22:06.670
[laughter] Well, if my job is to take solar
energy and metabolize it into decomposable

00:22:06.670 --> 00:22:13.400
biomass, carbon sequestering biomass, where
of those three stages do I want grass more

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:16.279
often than not?

00:22:16.279 --> 00:22:17.490
Teenage.

00:22:17.490 --> 00:22:26.210
Not nursing home into senescence and not diaper
into trying to toddle, but teenage all right?

00:22:26.210 --> 00:22:32.150
And so, if the grass is allowed to just grow
and get old and die, it shuts down the photo

00:22:32.150 --> 00:22:34.770
synthetic thing.

00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:40.290
If it stays very diaper-ish, it can never
really kick into high gear.

00:22:40.290 --> 00:22:46.350
And so, the herbivore was nature's way before
mowing machines and before cheap energy was

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:55.240
nature's way of pruning the biomass to restart
the rapid biomass accumulation.

00:22:55.240 --> 00:23:04.789
An herbivore is an ecological biomass accumulation
restart button.

00:23:04.789 --> 00:23:09.080
That's the role of herbivores in nature, all
right?

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:17.289
And when we go to grass finished beef, grass
finished lamb, we reaffirm that normal role

00:23:17.289 --> 00:23:20.090
of the herbivore ecology in nature.

00:23:20.090 --> 00:23:24.070
We're the first culture -- and I'm almost
done -- we're the first culture that views

00:23:24.070 --> 00:23:30.900
children as liabilities instead of assets.

00:23:30.900 --> 00:23:36.130
All cultures in history viewed children as
a blessing.

00:23:36.130 --> 00:23:41.360
Today we talk about the cost of raising a
child.

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:50.370
You know, this is the first generation which
the average child has not had domestic chores.

00:23:50.370 --> 00:24:01.600
You know, kids used to grow up weeding the
garden, picking beans, helping can applesauce.

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:04.850
Helping to cook.

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:07.360
Today we call that child abuse.

00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:08.929
[laughter]

00:24:08.929 --> 00:24:16.130
&gt;&gt;Joel: And I would suggest -- and I know
I'm speaking into the heart of our electronic,

00:24:16.130 --> 00:24:21.410
plugged in, techno-glitzy world and so I'm
doing a dance with you here and I'm not a

00:24:21.410 --> 00:24:23.260
Luddite and I love technology.

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:32.230
I love microchip, electric fencing and energizers,
UV stabilized, you know, canvasses and nursery

00:24:32.230 --> 00:24:38.160
and polyethylene black plastic pipe and stainless
steel and refrigeration and there's a lot

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:40.080
of cool things we've got today, all right?

00:24:40.080 --> 00:24:45.179
But I want to tell you something.

00:24:45.179 --> 00:24:55.440
Human self-actualization, human self-affirmation,
I think, is actually encouraged and stimulated

00:24:55.440 --> 00:25:04.400
when we viscerally participate in the physical
elements of life.

00:25:04.400 --> 00:25:09.940
And there is no comparison with looking back
at the end of the day and seeing gleaming

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:15.919
gleaming jars of fresh-made, canned salsa
for example, sitting on the shelf that you've

00:25:15.919 --> 00:25:20.360
picked the tomatoes and you've sliced and
diced and you've smelled it and you've been

00:25:20.360 --> 00:25:26.160
viscerally involved, touching, smelling, moving
it, and preserving it for the future.

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:31.020
There's nothing that compares with the sight
and the ability to participate and have a

00:25:31.020 --> 00:25:40.820
visceral relationship with that production
on the shelf compared to being the top performer

00:25:40.820 --> 00:25:45.460
in the latest video game.

00:25:45.460 --> 00:25:48.179
One is just cyber.

00:25:48.179 --> 00:25:49.980
And we see it in our interns.

00:25:49.980 --> 00:25:57.190
We've had interns come out of Dilbert-cubicle
type situations.

00:25:57.190 --> 00:26:03.710
And they get there and they describe with
trembling lips and deep emotion that for the

00:26:03.710 --> 00:26:14.751
first time they were able to build something
that they could touch, sense, feel, and hear

00:26:14.751 --> 00:26:20.210
the voices of their team members in person.

00:26:20.210 --> 00:26:22.510
Powerful self-actualization.

00:26:22.510 --> 00:26:30.279
And finally, we're the first culture that
has devoted so much time and energy to a national

00:26:30.279 --> 00:26:37.980
food police -- the food police -- you know
about the food police -- we call them the

00:26:37.980 --> 00:26:39.470
food safety people.

00:26:39.470 --> 00:26:41.240
I call them the food police.

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:46.380
Who, for the first time in human history,
have told a culture that you know it's perfectly

00:26:46.380 --> 00:26:53.250
safe to eat Mountain Dew, Twinkies and Cocoa
Puffs but that raw milk, compost-grown raw

00:26:53.250 --> 00:27:01.440
potatoes and Aunt Mathilda's pickles now that's
deadly [laughter] And so, I want to end -- because

00:27:01.440 --> 00:27:08.110
of this setting-- , I want to end with a thought
about food innovation.

00:27:08.110 --> 00:27:13.760
Because folks, what has become normal in our
culture I'm suggesting, you know, DiGiorno's

00:27:13.760 --> 00:27:23.720
frozen pizza, concentrated animal feeding
operations farms with no trespassing signs,

00:27:23.720 --> 00:27:28.149
food production models that you have to walk
through sheep dip and put on hazardous materials

00:27:28.149 --> 00:27:37.409
suit to go visit, it's not food worth eating
and it's created a toxic landscape.

00:27:37.409 --> 00:27:42.490
Just try living down river from a concentrated
animal feeding operation or from a mono-speciated

00:27:42.490 --> 00:27:45.980
spraying operation in the San Joaquin valley.

00:27:45.980 --> 00:27:47.580
We know about this.

00:27:47.580 --> 00:27:55.039
There are many of us who believe that much
of our pathogenicity, our type two diabetes,

00:27:55.039 --> 00:28:00.160
the fact that the U.S. leads the world in
the five chronic debilitating diseases of

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:04.230
cancer and diabetes and these things.

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:09.730
There's a reason why, that there's a connection
here because we lead the world in creating

00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:12.899
an abnormal food system.

00:28:12.899 --> 00:28:22.289
Now, if we're going to return our food system
and our landscape policy to a more normal

00:28:22.289 --> 00:28:29.490
sustainable regenerative system I would suggest
that it's going to require the same kind of

00:28:29.490 --> 00:28:37.400
innovation that Google enjoys today bringing
innovation to the world.

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:38.909
How does innovation happen?

00:28:38.909 --> 00:28:44.090
It happens in embryonic prototypes.

00:28:44.090 --> 00:28:50.520
The beginning of Google is not a 15,000 person
campus in California.

00:28:50.520 --> 00:28:56.960
The beginning of Google is a couple wild ideas
with lunatics sitting on their little computers

00:28:56.960 --> 00:29:01.710
fooling around with stuff and dreaming and
thinking.

00:29:01.710 --> 00:29:04.149
But starting small.

00:29:04.149 --> 00:29:10.919
And so, what we've got right now is a desperate
need in our food system to free up the innovators

00:29:10.919 --> 00:29:12.419
at the bottom.

00:29:12.419 --> 00:29:19.340
Farmers like us that are returning with high-tech,
techno-glitzy stuff like electric fencing

00:29:19.340 --> 00:29:24.390
and 4 wheel drive diesel tractors, with front
end loaders and chipper shredders, large scale

00:29:24.390 --> 00:29:26.750
composting and all that kind of stuff.

00:29:26.750 --> 00:29:36.220
But taking that heritage normal biological
cycling with a healthy dose of appropriate

00:29:36.220 --> 00:29:43.080
technology, marrying the two together and
coming with an innovative anecdote -- antidote

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:51.000
not anecdote -- antidote to the problems we
face in our ecology in our food system.

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:57.240
And we have to be able to start from the tailgate
of a pickup truck; from an innovative kitchen

00:29:57.240 --> 00:29:58.419
in our homes.

00:29:58.419 --> 00:30:03.600
We have to be able to start there to access
our neighborhoods and our communities with

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:10.170
innovative antidotes to what Wal-Mart and
Costco are offering us.

00:30:10.170 --> 00:30:12.470
And so, that's just as much as I'll say.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:14.260
You can ask more questions about the food
police.

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:16.100
That's as much as I'll say right now.

00:30:16.100 --> 00:30:22.340
But it is absolutely an innovation thread
that runs through everything and that's why

00:30:22.340 --> 00:30:31.510
innovation always occurs in the economic sectors
of least governmental penetration.

00:30:31.510 --> 00:30:38.480
And that's why government regulation is stifling
true innovation and antidotes to the problems

00:30:38.480 --> 00:30:39.480
of society.

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:44.460
And so, that's all I'll say right there about
the food police.

00:30:44.460 --> 00:30:46.159
We can go onto more questions and answer.

00:30:46.159 --> 00:30:47.789
I think I'd like to stop right there.

00:30:47.789 --> 00:30:52.390
That gives you a few tidbits of some of the
things that are in this book "Folks, This

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:53.390
Ain't Normal".

