my problem?

00:36:29.670 --> 00:36:31.150
What's my excuse?"

00:36:31.150 --> 00:36:38.680
And the fact is if the 98 percent of the people
who could do something would do it, it would

00:36:38.680 --> 00:36:43.740
so fundamentally change the fringes that the
argument would change in a way that we can't

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:44.740
even imagine.

00:36:44.740 --> 00:36:54.770
You know, it's like people with a 4-acre suburban
lawn coming together at their garden club

00:36:54.770 --> 00:37:05.320
meeting and stewing about, you know, the 4-child
single mom in Harlem that can't grow a garden.

00:37:05.320 --> 00:37:07.020
Why don't all you people grow a garden?

00:37:07.020 --> 00:37:10.340
We got 35 million acres of lawn in this country.

00:37:10.340 --> 00:37:15.540
36 million acres growing food and housing
and recreational horses.

00:37:15.540 --> 00:37:16.990
That's 71 million acres.

00:37:16.990 --> 00:37:21.030
That's enough to feed the whole country without
a single farm.

00:37:21.030 --> 00:37:25.830
So the point is every one who can should.

00:37:25.830 --> 00:37:30.710
And if everyone who could would, it would
so fundamentally change the parameters of

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:34.820
the argument that we can't even imagine the
innovation that would punch out the other

00:37:34.820 --> 00:37:36.130
side.

00:37:36.130 --> 00:37:42.240
And, if it became more normal again, a lot
of things would happen -- economies of scale

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:46.060
just regular things that happen when something
becomes more normal.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:47.570
Next question?

00:37:47.570 --> 00:37:48.570
Yes.

00:37:48.570 --> 00:37:50.590
&gt;&gt; Male #2: Hi.

00:37:50.590 --> 00:37:52.220
I'm from the big island of Hawaii.

00:37:52.220 --> 00:37:54.610
I have a farm and a community there.

00:37:54.610 --> 00:37:56.600
We've had -- we integrate chickens.

00:37:56.600 --> 00:37:57.630
We make biochar.

00:37:57.630 --> 00:37:59.150
We generate all our inputs.

00:37:59.150 --> 00:38:00.150
It's all very lovely.

00:38:00.150 --> 00:38:01.180
&gt;&gt;Joel: Wow, you are weird.

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:02.180
Okay.

00:38:02.180 --> 00:38:03.180
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Yeah.

00:38:03.180 --> 00:38:04.180
Yeah.

00:38:04.180 --> 00:38:06.650
&gt;&gt;Male #2: A lot of us here are technologists.

00:38:06.650 --> 00:38:12.900
And sometimes when technologists get into
the carbon, we geek out on agriculture.

00:38:12.900 --> 00:38:14.030
&gt;&gt;Joel: Absolutely.

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:15.720
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Anyhow.

00:38:15.720 --> 00:38:23.650
Ultimately though, like many people in agriculturally
sustainable parts of the world, it's not economically

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:24.650
sustainable.

00:38:24.650 --> 00:38:27.910
We weren't able to for instance build a house
for our growing family.

00:38:27.910 --> 00:38:33.750
So like many many families one of us has to
leave and go to the city -- or Google in my

00:38:33.750 --> 00:38:41.290
case -- and be either wash cars of rich people
or be a software engineer -- my case -- and

00:38:41.290 --> 00:38:44.530
send the money home to the farm.

00:38:44.530 --> 00:38:48.220
This is like -- it's a -- it's common.

00:38:48.220 --> 00:38:50.650
It feels -- it's tragic in a way.

00:38:50.650 --> 00:38:57.220
I mean, I would love to be there with my chickens
and grass and everything.

00:38:57.220 --> 00:39:05.310
But is this -- could you say some words about
the people who have to leave the farms to

00:39:05.310 --> 00:39:06.940
make it work?

00:39:06.940 --> 00:39:10.280
Because the system is stacked against actually
doing it the right way.

00:39:10.280 --> 00:39:11.280
&gt;&gt;Joel: Yes, yes.

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:13.450
Well, if you would like me to, I would say,
" bless you my son.."

00:39:13.450 --> 00:39:15.940
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Thank you.

00:39:15.940 --> 00:39:17.340
Amen.

00:39:17.340 --> 00:39:25.620
&gt;&gt;Joel: But in actuality, we haven't gotten
where we are overnight and we won't get out

00:39:25.620 --> 00:39:27.330
of it overnight.

00:39:27.330 --> 00:39:34.270
And as you know, all innovation requires disturbance.

00:39:34.270 --> 00:39:35.800
We know that.

00:39:35.800 --> 00:39:42.251
All succession, all, you know, freshing up
whether it's for ideas, technology, policy

00:39:42.251 --> 00:39:46.110
-- it all requires disturbance.

00:39:46.110 --> 00:39:51.710
And so, what you're going through in your
life right now is the disturbance of an innovative

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:55.540
idea that you have brought to your home, your
family.

00:39:55.540 --> 00:39:58.010
Chance are you didn't grow up on a farm.

00:39:58.010 --> 00:40:04.040
Chances are you have this green bug in your
genes somewhere, you know?

00:40:04.040 --> 00:40:08.860
Both Gen and Jean.

00:40:08.860 --> 00:40:14.500
You have this thing that is wanting you to
move forward that way.

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:17.020
And a lot of people do.

00:40:17.020 --> 00:40:23.270
A lot of people really want to do something
with their hands as a craftsman or an artisan.

00:40:23.270 --> 00:40:34.720
And I think our culture has failed the blue
collar craftsmanship of our age by worshiping

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:44.320
just intellectual, academic, cerebral pursuits
without appreciating the balancing groundedness

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:52.810
that calluses and not to mention immunofunction
occurs when we assault our immunofunction

00:40:52.810 --> 00:40:58.280
with exercise with calluses and splinters
and dirt under our fingernails or grease or

00:40:58.280 --> 00:40:59.280
whatever.

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:05.720
And so, what you see, then, is you see people
with physical, visceral hobbies whether it's

00:41:05.720 --> 00:41:11.680
building sailboats or gardening or doing something.

00:41:11.680 --> 00:41:14.560
We've got people now learning to cut meat
in big cities.

00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:16.980
It used to be like big Tupperware parties.

00:41:16.980 --> 00:41:18.740
Now it's meat-cutting parties.

00:41:18.740 --> 00:41:21.660
[laughter] Because people want to get in there
and touch it, sense it.

00:41:21.660 --> 00:41:25.490
It's the Lexus and the olive tree phenomenon.

00:41:25.490 --> 00:41:29.830
And so, in a place like this you see it very
acutely.

00:41:29.830 --> 00:41:35.700
And so, I think what you're trying to do is
absolutely phenomenal and laudable and I think

00:41:35.700 --> 00:41:39.840
there are principles that hopefully -- I wrote
a book "You Can Farm".

00:41:39.840 --> 00:41:40.840
&gt;&gt;Male #2: I read it.

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:47.130
&gt;&gt;Joel: That can hopefully help stimulate
some creativity in how to jump start that

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:48.130
forward.

00:41:48.130 --> 00:41:53.330
But at the end of the day what you're trying
to do is leave a legacy that has moved us

00:41:53.330 --> 00:41:56.960
innovatively in some direction.

00:41:56.960 --> 00:42:00.140
And maybe you won't accomplish it completely
even in your lifetime.

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:07.460
In fact, I've heard, if a vision can be accomplished
in your lifetime, it's too small.

00:42:07.460 --> 00:42:11.110
My dad used to say, if you don't suck a seed
just suck and suck and suck until you do suck

00:42:11.110 --> 00:42:12.110
a seed.

00:42:12.110 --> 00:42:16.770
So just keep after it.

00:42:16.770 --> 00:42:21.050
And remember that anything worth doing is
worth doing poorly first.

00:42:21.050 --> 00:42:24.020
We've all heard Grandma.

00:42:24.020 --> 00:42:25.370
We come do adulthood.

00:42:25.370 --> 00:42:28.910
You know we're children and we're willing
to experiment with things.

00:42:28.910 --> 00:42:35.830
And we come to adulthood and we become paralyzed
with analysis and fear because we can hear

00:42:35.830 --> 00:42:40.560
Grandma over our shoulder, "if it's worth
doing, it's worth doing right."

00:42:40.560 --> 00:42:44.310
And the fact is, nobody does it right the
first time.

00:42:44.310 --> 00:42:45.310
Nobody.

00:42:45.310 --> 00:42:51.430
I mean, it would be equivalent to, you know,
to going to a family shindig and here's a

00:42:51.430 --> 00:42:58.150
little toddler and the first time Janie tries
to stand up, she gets up on a chair she's

00:42:58.150 --> 00:43:00.740
wide eyed, "Oh look Janie's starting to stand."

00:43:00.740 --> 00:43:06.590
Of course she gets this great big grin, she
loses her grip on the chair and falls down

00:43:06.590 --> 00:43:09.510
on her diaper and all the adults gather around
and say "Janie, if you can't walk any better

00:43:09.510 --> 00:43:11.610
than that just quit".

00:43:11.610 --> 00:43:13.921
[laughter] We don't do that do we?

00:43:13.921 --> 00:43:16.520
We say, "oh, wow, she's doing."

00:43:16.520 --> 00:43:21.320
And the fact is all of us toddle first.

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:26.190
And so, if it's worth doing, it's worth doing
poorly first and just be encouraged by that

00:43:26.190 --> 00:43:28.630
and keep going after it.

00:43:28.630 --> 00:43:34.790
&gt;&gt;Female #1: Your answer to -- so Kevin's
question was more or less -- there's a lot

00:43:34.790 --> 00:43:39.250
of people out there who can't afford to eat
well and your answer was well they can afford

00:43:39.250 --> 00:43:41.560
to eat well they just choose not to.

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:46.870
So how do you change the mind set and convince
them that it's something worth doing as opposed

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:48.990
to something that's not worth doing.

00:43:48.990 --> 00:43:53.070
And I have a second question which is, if
you were king for a day and could change three

00:43:53.070 --> 00:43:59.360
policies or behaviors or do three things to
fix the U.S. food system what three things

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:00.680
would those be.

00:44:00.680 --> 00:44:02.000
&gt;&gt;Joel: Oh my.

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:05.310
You moved this question -- okay.

00:44:05.310 --> 00:44:07.750
So we'll go to your king for a day one.

00:44:07.750 --> 00:44:13.360
Yeah, because I do believe that it is a mind
set.

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:14.880
I did a class for a college.

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:20.600
It was a real elite girl's private college
on global food issues.

00:44:20.600 --> 00:44:24.180
The professor of global food issues wanted
me to come and be a guest lecture.

00:44:24.180 --> 00:44:26.290
I said, "let us do something different.

00:44:26.290 --> 00:44:31.300
Get us a classroom with a cooking range in
it.

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:35.090
You go get some salsa and some good local
artisanal cheese.

00:44:35.090 --> 00:44:39.590
I'll bring some apple juice from our neighbor's
biological apple orchard.

00:44:39.590 --> 00:44:42.580
I'll bring some eggs and some skillets okay?

00:44:42.580 --> 00:44:46.870
So we went in there and I did omelets for
these college students.

00:44:46.870 --> 00:44:49.630
You know, sixty-second omelets.

00:44:49.630 --> 00:44:51.500
And we had the salsa; we had this cheese.

00:44:51.500 --> 00:44:53.960
We had this apple juice to die for.

00:44:53.960 --> 00:44:56.230
It's cold pressed; it's got an inch of sediment
on the bottom.

00:44:56.230 --> 00:45:01.260
You have to be careful eating it because you
could guzzle it and ooh, I just ate six apples.

00:45:01.260 --> 00:45:03.410
And you have 24 hours to work through this
event.

00:45:03.410 --> 00:45:12.260
[laughter] But anyway, we did these wonderful
omelets for a buck 50 a plate in two minutes

00:45:12.260 --> 00:45:13.490
per.

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:14.490
So I asked the students.

00:45:14.490 --> 00:45:18.380
I said so -- because college students are
always forlorn no money, no time, blah, blah,

00:45:18.380 --> 00:45:19.380
blah.

00:45:19.380 --> 00:45:20.920
I said so how many of you watched a movie
this week.

00:45:20.920 --> 00:45:22.080
All of them.

00:45:22.080 --> 00:45:25.700
How many of you put money in a vending machine
this week?

00:45:25.700 --> 00:45:28.370
All of them.

00:45:28.370 --> 00:45:29.650
Okay?

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:30.930
See?

00:45:30.930 --> 00:45:33.530
We live in a culture that's all about victimhood.

00:45:33.530 --> 00:45:35.810
Victims, victims, victims.

00:45:35.810 --> 00:45:39.950
I mean, and we're hard wired to remember what
stops us not what makes us go.

00:45:39.950 --> 00:45:44.980
That's why we call them stoplights and not
go lights, okay?

00:45:44.980 --> 00:45:47.110
So we dwell on the negative.

00:45:47.110 --> 00:45:48.720
We dwell on the negative.

00:45:48.720 --> 00:45:53.820
And so, the positive part of the question,
if I were king for the day what couple of

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:58.380
policies would I do to really move this forward?

00:45:58.380 --> 00:46:01.340
Ooh, that is a big one.

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:07.370
The first one I would do, is to eliminate
all farm subsidies.

00:46:07.370 --> 00:46:10.190
All subsidies.

00:46:10.190 --> 00:46:12.450
All these things that -- and you know what?

00:46:12.450 --> 00:46:16.120
There are a lot of things that aren't overt
farm subsidies.

00:46:16.120 --> 00:46:20.730
They're kind of sweetheart deals.

00:46:20.730 --> 00:46:27.340
You know, things that, for example, make it
cheaper to bring a container load of apples

00:46:27.340 --> 00:46:33.570
from China than pick apples from our own trees.

00:46:33.570 --> 00:46:40.380
Because that's, you know, if you use -- because
of all the laws regarding that.

00:46:40.380 --> 00:46:41.951
So I would certainly eliminate all the subsidies.

00:46:41.951 --> 00:46:47.910
The second thing I would do, is amend the
constitution with a food emancipation proclamation.

00:46:47.910 --> 00:46:52.130
[laughter] And I would grant every citizen
of the United States.

00:46:52.130 --> 00:46:57.020
And I am dead -- it's funny but I am dead
serious about this -- I would grant every

00:46:57.020 --> 00:47:02.510
citizen of America the right to food freedom
of choice.

00:47:02.510 --> 00:47:04.180
We do not have that in our culture.

00:47:04.180 --> 00:47:10.400
And the Food and Drug Administration now,
in response to several suits filed by the

00:47:10.400 --> 00:47:15.470
farm to consumer legal defense fund, which
I call the NRA of food choice in our country.

00:47:15.470 --> 00:47:18.540
And everybody should join it because I want
it to be as big as the NRA.

00:47:18.540 --> 00:47:24.040
Because you see we've been granted the freedom
to own guns, worship, assemble and speak.

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:28.300
Well, what good is it to have those freedoms
if you don't have the freedom to choose the

00:47:28.300 --> 00:47:35.770
fuel to feed your 3 trillion member internal
community of beings that fuels you to go,

00:47:35.770 --> 00:47:38.010
shoot, pray, and preach?

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:43.370
[laughter] It happen only reason that our
founders did not give us the freedom of food

00:47:43.370 --> 00:47:51.151
choice is because they couldn't have imagined
a day in which you couldn't, you know, buy

00:47:51.151 --> 00:47:56.240
raw milk from your neighbor and California
has now, you know, incarcerated these three

00:47:56.240 --> 00:48:04.000
folks down in Los Angeles for having the audacity
to take their herd share goat milk from their

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:09.330
own animals off the farm and drink it in their
own homes with their own families.

00:48:09.330 --> 00:48:11.340
Now, folks this is tyranny.

00:48:11.340 --> 00:48:16.970
And we're supposedly fighting tyranny around
the world with our military while our own

00:48:16.970 --> 00:48:25.280
USDA food police sends swat teams out to farmers
and confiscate food out of domestic freezers

00:48:25.280 --> 00:48:31.340
to keep families from being able to eat foods
of their choice.

00:48:31.340 --> 00:48:37.940
So I would emancipate food from its enslavement
by Monsanto's agenda.

00:48:37.940 --> 00:48:42.300
And anyone who thinks Monsanto is your friend,
think again.

00:48:42.300 --> 00:48:44.820
You know, we have trespass law in this country.

00:48:44.820 --> 00:48:49.360
If I came to your house or your yard and dumped
a bunch of garbage on your lawn that you didn't

00:48:49.360 --> 00:48:55.570
want, I'd probably -- the prosecuting attorney
would come against me for trespassing violations,

00:48:55.570 --> 00:48:56.690
right?

00:48:56.690 --> 00:49:03.850
But Monsanto can go and dump promiscuous pollen.

00:49:03.850 --> 00:49:05.980
Those are interesting words.

00:49:05.980 --> 00:49:22.540
[laughter] Promiscuous pollen that runs rampant
around the community creating sexual orgies

00:49:22.540 --> 00:49:34.680
in my plants with life forms of garbage that
I don't want and our country -- our own president

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:42.970
-- our Democratic president thinks that I
should have to pay Monsanto a royalty for

00:49:42.970 --> 00:49:49.180
the privilege of their promiscuous pollen.

00:49:49.180 --> 00:49:52.030
This ain't normal.

00:49:52.030 --> 00:49:53.260
So.

00:49:53.260 --> 00:49:57.420
I would absolutely say, "you know what?

00:49:57.420 --> 00:49:58.820
You own you".

00:49:58.820 --> 00:50:01.170
And you can word it however you want to.

00:50:01.170 --> 00:50:09.430
But I would say every person is now -- if
you want to take responsibility for your own

00:50:09.430 --> 00:50:14.840
person hood and your own 3 trillion member
of internal community of beings, you can do

00:50:14.840 --> 00:50:15.840
it.

00:50:15.840 --> 00:50:17.360
You can do it.

00:50:17.360 --> 00:50:18.880
[laughter] You know.

00:50:18.880 --> 00:50:24.580
Now, if you don't want to and you still want
a USDA stamp on all the food you eat to certify

00:50:24.580 --> 00:50:31.040
that it's gone through the industrial food
fraternity, that's fine with me.

00:50:31.040 --> 00:50:33.650
And you will find me -- I will not be picketing
McDonalds.

00:50:33.650 --> 00:50:35.660
I will not be picketing the World Trade Organization.

00:50:35.660 --> 00:50:38.130
I will not be picketing Monsanto.

00:50:38.130 --> 00:50:50.590
What I want is to let we native Americans
who honor heritage indigenous foods to be

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:54.880
able to eat it and for you to be able to buy
it.

00:50:54.880 --> 00:51:03.950
And if we did that, folks, if we did that,
you would see an explosion of cottage industry

00:51:03.950 --> 00:51:08.270
and domestic food systems like you cannot
imagine.

00:51:08.270 --> 00:51:09.550
Everywhere I go around the country.

00:51:09.550 --> 00:51:12.030
This is a very unusual group for me to talk
to.

00:51:12.030 --> 00:51:18.270
My bread and butter group have been sustainable
ago groups farmers and greenie type food people.

00:51:18.270 --> 00:51:26.690
And everywhere I go there is just this almost
like a bull in the stall at the rodeo right

00:51:26.690 --> 00:51:29.580
before they let him out or a horse right before
the horse race.

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:38.260
There's just this chafing at the bit ready
to make egg noodles or quiche from my garden

00:51:38.260 --> 00:51:45.540
produce or lacto-fermented sauerkraut or charcuterie
or artisanal cheese.

00:51:45.540 --> 00:51:50.610
There's this -- people are just nuts about
this.

00:51:50.610 --> 00:52:02.990
But in between them and their neighbor and
you is this huge food police that says, "Oh,

00:52:02.990 --> 00:52:06.610
you can't make pickles in your house and sell
it to a neighbor, that's manufacturing.

00:52:06.610 --> 00:52:11.090
You live in a residential community."

00:52:11.090 --> 00:52:16.690
So I have a lady in Texas that told me she
got fined by her homeowner's association because

00:52:16.690 --> 00:52:22.080
there's antifarming language in her homeowner's
association and she grew a tomato plant in

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:27.050
her vegetable, I mean flower garden and that's
farming.

00:52:27.050 --> 00:52:35.000
So we have created -- we have taken our western,
Greco-Roman, reductionist, linear, compartmentalized,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:41.040
fragmentized, systematized, disconnected,
individualized, parts-oriented, kind of thinking

00:52:41.040 --> 00:52:51.750
to an unbelievable philosophical apartheid
and I think that those of us who want to come

00:52:51.750 --> 00:52:57.640
back together in a more eastern holistic,
we're all related, and let me own my own body

00:52:57.640 --> 00:53:04.730
-- those of us who want to do that and live
in our tepees and have our medicine man and

00:53:04.730 --> 00:53:08.250
educate as runners instead of mathematics.

00:53:08.250 --> 00:53:17.350
Those of us who wanted to do that, should
be able to opt out of the greater cultural

00:53:17.350 --> 00:53:22.520
that normalcy may not vanish from this side
of our world.

00:53:22.520 --> 00:53:23.520
Question.

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:27.980
&gt;&gt;Male #3: Well, how to follow that one up?

00:53:27.980 --> 00:53:33.530
So it seems that you're describing a really
wedged situation here with the laws and how

00:53:33.530 --> 00:53:34.910
the money flows.

00:53:34.910 --> 00:53:38.931
And you know one of the characteristics of
a wedge like that is that the people who are

00:53:38.931 --> 00:53:43.970
benefiting the most are the beneficiaries
and they have power.

00:53:43.970 --> 00:53:45.430
How do you break a cycle like that.

00:53:45.430 --> 00:53:46.810
&gt;&gt;Joel: How do you break a cycle?

00:53:46.810 --> 00:53:49.600
Well, that's why I didn't say -- see?

00:53:49.600 --> 00:53:53.710
Notice I didn't say if I were king for a day,
I would shut down Monsanto.

00:53:53.710 --> 00:53:56.000
See, a lot of my friends would say that.

00:53:56.000 --> 00:54:00.590
If I were king for a day I would outlaw concentrated
animal feeding operations or I would outlaw

00:54:00.590 --> 00:54:01.690
-- you know what I'm saying?

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:03.980
Or I would outlaw genetic modification or
whatever.

00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:04.980
You see?

00:54:04.980 --> 00:54:06.580
I didn't say any of those things.

00:54:06.580 --> 00:54:11.160
I really believe and I think I'm at home in
this company here to say this.

00:54:11.160 --> 00:54:19.580
I really believe that the greatest innovation
and the greatest opportunity is when we allow

00:54:19.580 --> 00:54:27.410
people to self-actualize their own individual
expression.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:33.100
That's why on our farm we create habitats
to preserve and enhance the pigness of the

00:54:33.100 --> 00:54:37.700
pig, the chickenness of the chicken, and the
tomatoness of the tomato.

00:54:37.700 --> 00:54:45.770
It's in that environment of phenotypical distinctive
expression that you capture the essence of

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:51.400
the person and the essence of the gifts and
talents they bring to the table.

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:53.550
And so, yes, it is a wedge.

00:54:53.550 --> 00:55:02.030
And that's why I think rather than try to
regulate out and cherry pick what we don't

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:04.240
like and regulate that out.

00:55:04.240 --> 00:55:14.420
If we just allow the people -- I mean, right
here the people who want to eat differently

00:55:14.420 --> 00:55:21.290
and buy differently and by one meal at a time
create a different landscape for their grandchildren.

00:55:21.290 --> 00:55:34.200
If we allow them to do that, it would just
completely topple Monsanto, Tyson, Ciba Geigy.

00:55:34.200 --> 00:55:40.720
The only reason they're able to enjoy their
position at the top is because they're protected

00:55:40.720 --> 00:55:48.260
from competition at the bottom that is absolutely
-- that has absolutely jumped ship.

00:55:48.260 --> 00:55:57.780
You know, very few people I think really trust
Kraft Food to take care of them anymore.

00:55:57.780 --> 00:55:59.470
We've been there, done that, okay?

00:55:59.470 --> 00:56:00.940
And look where we are.

00:56:00.940 --> 00:56:06.670
We've exchanged 18 percent food costs and
9 percent health care to 9 percent food costs

00:56:06.670 --> 00:56:08.090
and 18 percent health care.

00:56:08.090 --> 00:56:11.820
We've been there done that.

00:56:11.820 --> 00:56:17.480
Just like people who are looking for breast-feeding,
Lamaze, home schooling, free food in an institutional

00:56:17.480 --> 00:56:18.480
setting.

00:56:18.480 --> 00:56:22.890
Who would have dreamed of this five years
ago?

00:56:22.890 --> 00:56:25.600
Who would have dreamed of it, okay?

00:56:25.600 --> 00:56:36.510
This is indicative of an entire desire to
not entrust the current powers that be with

00:56:36.510 --> 00:56:40.760
my body, my food, and my being.

00:56:40.760 --> 00:56:47.890
And so, what we need to do is just free up
that -- free up that move, okay?

00:56:47.890 --> 00:56:50.550
Let it go.

00:56:50.550 --> 00:56:56.660
And that's what scares the current big players
to death.

00:56:56.660 --> 00:57:02.820
But that's where I'm coming from freedom from
the bottom up not from regulation top down.

00:57:02.820 --> 00:57:04.830
And that's the difference.

00:57:04.830 --> 00:57:08.700
&gt;&gt; Liv Wu: I love finding this.

00:57:08.700 --> 00:57:12.300
And I want to read it and have you comment
on it.

00:57:12.300 --> 00:57:14.570
You call it "scaling up without selling your
soul."

00:57:14.570 --> 00:57:21.911
[reading] "Many successful entrepreneurial
startups morph into Wall Street empires that

00:57:21.911 --> 00:57:28.350
lose their distinctiveness and in the process
the business chews up and spits out its workers

00:57:28.350 --> 00:57:32.050
and founders in a mad scramble to dominate
something.

00:57:32.050 --> 00:57:38.450
Does middle ground exist between the calm
talking stick circle of indigenous circle

00:57:38.450 --> 00:57:44.960
of eastern tribal cultures and the mad scramble
frenzy of western capitalism.

00:57:44.960 --> 00:57:50.170
Or perhaps more to the point, in light of
recent Wall Street and economic developments,

00:57:50.170 --> 00:57:54.950
what values are more important than growth?

00:57:54.950 --> 00:57:58.990
Especially since cancer is growth."

00:57:58.990 --> 00:58:02.950
Please talk about this whether it's the food
chain or larger.

00:58:02.950 --> 00:58:04.840
&gt;&gt;Joel: Sure.

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:07.270
What she just read is something that I wrote
actually.

00:58:07.270 --> 00:58:15.320
You didn't say that I wrote it, but I wrote
that in response to -- I'm going to be very

00:58:15.320 --> 00:58:22.360
personal with you as our farm grew and as
our business grew we saw small entrepreneurial

00:58:22.360 --> 00:58:24.830
endeavors like ours be gobbled up.

00:58:24.830 --> 00:58:29.590
Look at organics today and look at the take
overs of the little innovative organic players

00:58:29.590 --> 00:58:33.540
in the game and they've been bought up by
the big food companies.

00:58:33.540 --> 00:58:40.980
We got scared frankly because we didn't want
to get gobbled up like this and sell our soul.

00:58:40.980 --> 00:58:51.500
And so, we developed a ten-step value statement
for Polyface farms that is a totally anti-Wall

00:58:51.500 --> 00:59:00.810
Street empire-building capitalistic value
statement that I gave first to Fortune 500

00:59:00.810 --> 00:59:05.150
middle managers at the Innovation Immersion
Summit in Phoenix, Arizona about five years

00:59:05.150 --> 00:59:06.430
ago.

00:59:06.430 --> 00:59:08.860
And I've given it several times.

00:59:08.860 --> 00:59:11.100
It probably should be a book.

00:59:11.100 --> 00:59:18.830
But as we looked at what is it that defines
us as a opposed to a typical, you know, a

00:59:18.830 --> 00:59:23.990
typical like global, Wall Street-type, capitalistic
corporation?

00:59:23.990 --> 00:59:25.450
There were distinctive that came about.

00:59:25.450 --> 00:59:29.170
And I won't give all ten of them to you but
I'll give a few.

00:59:29.170 --> 00:59:37.320
The first one was so we resolved ourselves
that we would never have a sales target.

00:59:37.320 --> 00:59:39.440
No sales target.

00:59:39.440 --> 00:59:42.500
We don't measure success by sales.

00:59:42.500 --> 00:59:46.590
As soon as you start measuring success by
sales or you create quotas or you say we want

00:59:46.590 --> 00:59:51.150
to be at this stage by such and such a date,
this many customers, this many sales.

00:59:51.150 --> 00:59:59.470
As soon as you do that, you begin looking
at people as commodities to buy, sell, and

00:59:59.470 --> 01:00:00.470
trade.

01:00:00.470 --> 01:00:03.140
In my scramble to the top of the heap.

01:00:03.140 --> 01:00:08.350
You know, notches in my hatchet if you will,
okay?

01:00:08.350 --> 01:00:17.410
And so, we want sales to be an organic -- almost
a serendipitous outgrowth of quality and service.

01:00:17.410 --> 01:00:21.460
And so, we don't assume -- this brings me
to my second segue.

01:00:21.460 --> 01:00:26.080
The second one is: we will never advertise.

01:00:26.080 --> 01:00:30.580
All growth, if it's going to be, has to come
from satisfied word of mouth.

01:00:30.580 --> 01:00:34.080
Now, it's fascinating to me that even the
companies that spend 2 million dollars for

01:00:34.080 --> 01:00:40.550
a thirty-second Superbowl ad still get 70
percent of their customers according to business

01:00:40.550 --> 01:00:44.430
journals by satisfied customers -- word of
mouth.

01:00:44.430 --> 01:00:46.930
It still works.

01:00:46.930 --> 01:00:52.600
And so -- and that is certainly a mantra here
at Google.

01:00:52.600 --> 01:00:54.930
It works.

01:00:54.930 --> 01:01:00.470
So we don't assume, if sales drop off, we
don't assume we're not spending enough on

01:01:00.470 --> 01:01:01.550
advertising.

01:01:01.550 --> 01:01:07.610
We assume that we must not be giving the quality
or service or whatever.

01:01:07.610 --> 01:01:08.610
Okay?

01:01:08.610 --> 01:01:09.610
In other words.

01:01:09.610 --> 01:01:15.570
And what this does is instead of immediately
making us look outside, it makes us look inside

01:01:15.570 --> 01:01:20.630
and we think that's healthy for the organism.

01:01:20.630 --> 01:01:27.050
Another one is that we will never patent or
copyright.

01:01:27.050 --> 01:01:29.630
Whoa -- talk about anti-Wall Street.

01:01:29.630 --> 01:01:30.770
Here's the deal.

01:01:30.770 --> 01:01:33.060
We want to be lean and mean.

01:01:33.060 --> 01:01:37.730
And if we never patent anything, then that
means, we have to stay lean and mean to stay

01:01:37.730 --> 01:01:39.800
ahead against the copiers.

01:01:39.800 --> 01:01:45.500
And if we can't stay one stride ahead of the
copiers, then we don't deserve to be in charge.

01:01:45.500 --> 01:01:49.970
Because really, all these ideas are just gifts.

01:01:49.970 --> 01:01:54.940
And I know -- boy, that's a real big one,
okay?

01:01:54.940 --> 01:01:59.690
Especially since this morning I was reading
about Steve Jobs and the antipathy between

01:01:59.690 --> 01:02:03.700
Apple and Google and I'm watching all of your
Apple computers here.

01:02:03.700 --> 01:02:08.840
[laughter] And realizing a lot of Google money
bought Apple computers.

01:02:08.840 --> 01:02:19.560
So anyway, the idea here is that innovation
really in a lot of ways is just -- is very

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:25.750
much a stroke of blessing, genius and epiphany.

01:02:25.750 --> 01:02:34.140
And so, the innovators should be sharp enough
to stay a little bit ahead of the copy catters.

01:02:34.140 --> 01:02:35.940
So those are just three.

01:02:35.940 --> 01:02:43.470
But there are ten of these that we have identified
-- one is defining our -- a fourth one is

01:02:43.470 --> 01:02:44.690
defining our market.

01:02:44.690 --> 01:02:47.730
We won't deliver more than four hours away
from the farm.

01:02:47.730 --> 01:02:52.740
Because four hours out and 4 hours back is
about as much as one person can drive in one

01:02:52.740 --> 01:02:53.740
day.

01:02:53.740 --> 01:02:57.690
Which creates an ability for transparency.

01:02:57.690 --> 01:03:00.310
We don't want to ship anywhere.

01:03:00.310 --> 01:03:02.070
We want people to come to the farm.

01:03:02.070 --> 01:03:08.790
We have a 24/7, 365 open door unannounced
policy.

01:03:08.790 --> 01:03:13.310
Instead of a no trespassing sign, we want
to put up a sign "trespassers will be impressed."

01:03:13.310 --> 01:03:20.000
[laughter] And that's our commitment to transparency.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:21.600
We're not concerned about copy catters.

01:03:21.600 --> 01:03:27.060
We're not concerned about diseases, because
our animals have an immune system.

01:03:27.060 --> 01:03:33.640
[laughter] We want people to come and viscerally
participate in this so that, when we sit down

01:03:33.640 --> 01:03:40.510
to dine to this intimate experience of dining,
there is a partner we've danced with prior

01:03:40.510 --> 01:03:43.610
to meal.

01:03:43.610 --> 01:03:45.460
And that creates integrity.

01:03:45.460 --> 01:03:47.760
Maybe one more question -- what's our time
like?

01:03:47.760 --> 01:03:48.760
One more and we're over?

01:03:48.760 --> 01:03:49.760
OK, one more.

01:03:49.760 --> 01:03:51.240
&gt;&gt;Male #4: Thank you Joel for everything you
do.

01:03:51.240 --> 01:03:52.710
Really really appreciate it.

01:03:52.710 --> 01:03:55.190
You mentioned the power of word of mouth.

01:03:55.190 --> 01:03:59.940
And that's definitely something we're working
on here at Google and aiming to make it better

01:03:59.940 --> 01:04:00.940
at.

01:04:00.940 --> 01:04:03.160
We've announced some things that are coming
along those lines.

01:04:03.160 --> 01:04:05.770
I think you'll find some people in this room
and this company that will be very willing

01:04:05.770 --> 01:04:08.920
to help you get your message out.

01:04:08.920 --> 01:04:11.890
Given your difficulty with the swipe card
at the hotel this morning is there anything

01:04:11.890 --> 01:04:16.580
we can do as a individuals or as a company
to help you get that message out.

01:04:16.580 --> 01:04:19.910
&gt;&gt;Joel: [chuckles] Thank you.

01:04:19.910 --> 01:04:25.780
I would say well for one is -- that's one
reason I like to write.

01:04:25.780 --> 01:04:30.830
Because to me, that is a way -- and this is
by the way available on audio and Kindle,

01:04:30.830 --> 01:04:32.980
you know -- this book.

01:04:32.980 --> 01:04:38.480
But to get this kind of thinking penetrated
into our culture.

01:04:38.480 --> 01:04:42.550
But you guys -- when you said you want to
help, you have a great big voice here.

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:45.010
You have a huge voice.

01:04:45.010 --> 01:04:50.930
And your voice to bring balance can be extremely
powerful.

01:04:50.930 --> 01:05:04.830
And so, I think that individually in your
ripple of influence, you can add things to

01:05:04.830 --> 01:05:12.980
the pot whether it's how you eat, where you
recreate, what you do, what you value as a

01:05:12.980 --> 01:05:15.510
individual and then as a corporation, as a
business.

01:05:15.510 --> 01:05:24.240
There are certainly things that you could
do -- like you're doing -- more of the same.

01:05:24.240 --> 01:05:28.730
And continuing to use your purchasing power
-- I mean, I'm hearing about buying whole

01:05:28.730 --> 01:05:29.730
animals.

01:05:29.730 --> 01:05:30.730
That's a big deal.

01:05:30.730 --> 01:05:32.280
So the cafes have to work together.

01:05:32.280 --> 01:05:37.180
This one does T-bones this one wants meatloaf
and so you get together and you use the whole

01:05:37.180 --> 01:05:38.180
animal.

01:05:38.180 --> 01:05:39.180
And you use some blemished fruit.

01:05:39.180 --> 01:05:41.990
And you use some blemished tomatoes.

01:05:41.990 --> 01:05:44.100
Maybe Google could start a cannery here.

01:05:44.100 --> 01:05:50.630
Maybe you could have some canning classes
and take this one step further in domestic

01:05:50.630 --> 01:05:54.740
food preparation to stimulate domestic culinary
arts.

01:05:54.740 --> 01:06:00.850
Because ultimately this big change is not
going to occur -- I mean, it can't occur just

01:06:00.850 --> 01:06:06.200
with the farmers and just with the food preparers
or chefs or processors.

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:12.490
It ultimately has to penetrate to the way
we live so that our homes -- rather than just

01:06:12.490 --> 01:06:17.420
-- and our kitchens -- rather than just being
a pit stop between everything that's important

01:06:17.420 --> 01:06:23.950
in life out there actually become an epicenter
of how we live, use our lives and our economic

01:06:23.950 --> 01:06:29.520
commerce that we domesticate our values.

01:06:29.520 --> 01:06:34.370
And that is something that all of us can work
on.

01:06:34.370 --> 01:06:39.150
And that's something I'm sure Google can continue
to work on when I hear about 3 hour commutes

01:06:39.150 --> 01:06:41.680
and that sort of thing.

01:06:41.680 --> 01:06:49.740
And so, you know, telecommuting, working from
home, those kinds of things are ways to move

01:06:49.740 --> 01:06:55.780
that -- to take this information economy and
move it to the next step which is the regenerative

01:06:55.780 --> 01:06:56.780
economy.

01:06:56.780 --> 01:06:58.430
That's the next step we've got to go.

01:06:58.430 --> 01:07:02.750
We've been the agrarian, we've been the industrial,
we've been the information, now we've got

01:07:02.750 --> 01:07:05.390
to move on to the regenerational economy.

01:07:05.390 --> 01:07:07.920
Okay, everybody.

01:07:07.920 --> 01:07:10.610
Thank you for letting me visit with you.

01:07:10.610 --> 01:07:11.610
